Rating: 3
I followed the recipe exactly, except that I added more kielbasa because I had it on hand and wanted to use it up. If you want to use the soup as a main course, it's certainly appropriate to add more sausage, depending on your appetite. The soup can stand on it's own without the sausage if you only want it as a starter. Just to put my 2 cents in, the roux won't do what it's intended to if you don't use all the butter that is called for. That may explain some of the other comments about the substance of the soup. I found that the roux thickened the soup very well. I would just suggest that you stir the soup from time to time after adding the roux to prevent it from sticking on the bottom of the pot. My husband and I had the soup for dinner tonight and it was completely satisfying and filling. I appreciate others' comments about it being a good, hearty soup for a cold, snowy evening and even though this is the "first day of spring", in Lake Placid, NY, it's a cold snowy evening! Although cold is a relative term as the cook from Minnesota can confirm. Spring doesn't really come here until May....but the summmers, short as they may be, are absolutely fabulous, and worth every minute of the wait for them to come! By the way, you can use any herb you want to flavor the soup: you're not tied to marjoram if you don't have it or don't like it. Use whatever herb you prefer.

